                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>ABC</m> has <m>AB = 6</m> cm, <m>BC = 8</m> cm, and <m>CA = 7</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle accurately. Extend side <m>AB</m> beyond <m>B</m> and side <m>AC</m> beyond <m>C</m> as dashed rays.</li>
                        <li>Construct the external bisector of angle <m>B</m> and the external bisector of angle <m>C</m>. Label their intersection <m>J_a</m>.</li>
                        <li>Draw the excircle opposite <m>A</m>. Measure <m>r_a</m>.</li>
                        <li>Verify your answer by calculation using <m>r_a = \Delta\,/\,(s-a)</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The final construction is:
                    <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr1">
                    <caption>Excircle opposite <m>A</m> for the 6-7-8 triangle, with external bisectors at <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET: AB=6, BC=8, CA=7 ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 8/0/C}
                          \tkzDefPoint(6,0){bR}
                          \tkzDefPoint(15,0){cR}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzInterCC(B,bR)(C,cR) \tkzGetPoints{A}{Ap}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](A) \tkzGetPoint{ABext}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](C) \tkzGetPoint{ACext}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{X}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,thick](B,ABext C,ACext)
                          \tkzDrawLine[add=0 and 0.1, blue!60](B,Ia)
                          \tkzDrawLine[add=0 and 0.1, blue!60](C,Ia)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[red,thin](Ia,X)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,X)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,X)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](Ia,X,C)
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below left](B){$A$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left](A){$B$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ia){$J_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](X){$X$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                To calculate <m>r_a</m>, we first find the triangle area <m>\Delta</m>. Noting that <m>s = \frac{6+8+7}{2} = 10.5</m>
                <md>
                    \Delta = \sqrt{10.5(10.5-6)(10.5-8)(10.5-7)} \approx 20.33
                </md>
                Hence
                <md>
                    r_a = \frac{\Delta}{s-a} = \frac{20.33}{10.5-8} \approx 8.132 \text{ cm}
                </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>ABC</m> has <m>AB = 3</m> cm, <m>BC = 4</m> cm, and <m>CA = 5</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Construct all three excircles, one opposite each vertex.</li>
                        <li>Measure each excircle radius. Which is the largest? Which is the smallest?</li>
                        <li>What relationship do you notice between the size of an excircle and the length of the side it is opposite?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr2">
                    <caption>All three excircles of a 3-4-5 triangle (<m>AB=3</m>, <m>BC=4</m>, <m>CA=5</m>).</caption>
                    <image width="75%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET: AB=3, BC=4, CA=5; right angle at A ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 3/0/B, 0/5/C}
                          \tkzDefPoint(4,0){bR}
                          \tkzDefPoint(8,0){cR}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzInterCC(B,bR)(C,cR) \tkzGetPoints{Bpos}{Bneg}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](B,C,A) \tkzGetPoints{Ib}{Xb}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](C,A,B) \tkzGetPoints{Ic}{Xc}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{FootA}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ib) \tkzGetPoint{FootB}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](Ic) \tkzGetPoint{FootC}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawLine[dashed, add=1.4 and 1.4](A,B)
                          \tkzDrawLine[dashed, add=1.4 and 1.4](B,C)
                          \tkzDrawLine[dashed, add=1.4 and 1.4](C,A)
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue](Ia,FootA)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue](Ib,FootB)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue](Ic,FootC)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,Ib,Ic)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$B$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$A$}
                          \tkzLabelPoints[left](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below right](Ia){$J_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[left](Ib){$J_c$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ic){$J_b$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <m>r_a = 2</m> cm, <m>r_b = 3</m> cm, <m>r_c = 6</m> cm. The largest excircle is opposite the shortest side; the smallest excircle is opposite the longest side.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-exradius-proof">            
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    In <xref ref="thm-exradius"/> we stated that the radius of the excircle opposite vertex <m>A</m> is given by <m>r_a = \Delta\,/\,(s-a)</m>, where <m>\Delta</m> is the area of the triangle, <m>s = \frac{a+b+c}{2}</m> is the semi-perimeter, and <m>a</m> is the length of side <m>BC</m>. We will prove this formula.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-theorem-ex-v1">
                <caption>The excircle opposite <m>A</m>: centre <m>J_a</m>, tangent to <m>BC</m> at <m>X</m> and to the extensions at <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>.</caption>
                <image width="85%">
                    <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                      %% --- SET ---
                      \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.5/A}
                      %% --- CALCULATE ---
                      \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](A) \tkzGetPoint{ABext}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](C) \tkzGetPoint{ACext}
                      \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                      \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{X}
                      \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--ABext](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Y}
                      \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Z}
                      %% --- DRAW ---
                      \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                      \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,thick](B,ABext C,ACext)
                      \tkzDrawSegments[red,thin](Ia,X Ia,Y Ia,Z)
                      \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,X)
                      \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,X,Y,Z)
                      %% --- MARK ---
                      \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,X,C)
                      \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,Y,B)
                      %% --- LABEL ---
                      \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$A$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[above left](A){$B$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ia){$J_a$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[below](X){$X$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[left](Y){$Y$}
                      \tkzLabelPoint[above](Z){$Z$}
                      \tkzLabelSegment[right](X,Ia){$r_a$}
                      \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,B){$c$}
                      \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,C){$a$}
                      \tkzLabelSegment[below left](B,C){$b$}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Explain why <m>AY = AX</m>, <m>BY = BZ</m>, and <m>CX = CZ</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Tangents to the excircle (at <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, and <m>Z</m>) to an external point (<m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> respectively) are equal in length, so <m>AY = AX</m>, <m>BY = BZ</m>, and <m>CX = CZ</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Given that <m>BZ + CZ = BC = a</m>, use (a) to find <m>BY</m>, <m>BZ</m>, <m>CZ</m> and <m>CX</m> in terms of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Starting with <m>AY = AX</m>, we can split up both lengths:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>AY \amp = AX</mrow>
                            <mrow>AB + BY \amp = AC + CX </mrow>
                            <mrow>c + BZ \amp = b + CZ</mrow>
                            <mrow>BZ \amp = b + CZ - c</mrow>
                        </md>
                        Where we used the fact from (a) that <m>BY = BZ</m> and <m>CX = CZ</m>. Now since <m>BZ+CZ = a</m>, we rewrite <m>CZ = a - BZ</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>BZ \amp = b + a - BZ - c</mrow>
                            <mrow>BZ \amp = \frac{a+b-c}{2} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Thus <m>BY = \frac{a+b-c}{2}</m> as well, and:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>CX = CZ = a - \frac{a+b-c}{2} = \frac{a+c-b}{2}</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Thus find <m>AY</m> and <m>AX</m> in terms of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Calculating <m>AY</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>AY \amp = AB + BY </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = c + \frac{a+b-c}{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{a+b+c}{2} = s </mrow>
                        </md>
                        And likewise for <m>AX</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> AX \amp = AC + CX </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = b + \frac{b+c-a}{2} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{a+b+c}{2} = s </mrow>
                        </md> 
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        We will find <m>r_a</m> by calculating the area of quadrilateral <m>ABCJ_a</m> in two ways. First, draw <m>AJ_a</m> and find the area of <m>ABCJ_a</m> as the sum of the areas of triangles <m>\triangle AXJ_a</m> and <m>\triangle AYJ_a</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-theorem-ex-v2">
                        <caption>The excircle opposite <m>A</m>: centre <m>J_a</m>, tangent to <m>BC</m> at <m>X</m> and to the extensions at <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="80%">
                            <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.5/A}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](A) \tkzGetPoint{ABext}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](C) \tkzGetPoint{ACext}
                            \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--ABext](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,thick](B,ABext C,ACext)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[red,thin](Ia,X Ia,Y Ia,Z)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, purple](B,Ia)
                            \tkzFillPolygon[purple!20,opacity=0.2](B,X,Ia)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,X,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,Y,B)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](A){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ia){$J_a$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](X){$X$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](Y){$Y$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](Z){$Z$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](X,Ia){$r_a$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,B){$c$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,C){$a$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below left](B,C){$b$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Since both <m>\triangle AXJ_a</m> and <m>\triangle AYJ_a</m> are right-angled at <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> respectively, and have height <m>r_a</m> (the radius of the excircle), their areas are:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \Delta_{AXJ_a} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AX \cdot r_a = \frac{1}{2}sr_a </mrow>
                            <mrow> \Delta_{AYJ_a} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AY \cdot r_a = \frac{1}{2}sr_a</mrow>
                        </md>
                        Therefore, the area of quadrilateral <m>ABCJ_a</m> is:
                        <md number="yes" xml:id="eq-exradius-proof-1">
                            \text{Area}(ABCJ_a) = 2 \cdot \frac{1}{2}sr_a = sr_a
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        For a different approach, draw <m>BJ_a</m> and <m>CJ_a</m> and consider the area of <m>ABCJ_a</m> as the sum of the areas of triangles <m>\triangle ABC</m> and the remaining triangles.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-theorem-ex-v3">
                        <caption>The excircle opposite <m>A</m>: centre <m>J_a</m>, tangent to <m>BC</m> at <m>X</m> and to the extensions at <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="85%">
                            <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C, 1.5/3.5/A}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](A) \tkzGetPoint{ABext}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center B ratio 2.1](C) \tkzGetPoint{ACext}
                            \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{X}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--ABext](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Y}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Z}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,thick](B,ABext C,ACext)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[red,thin](Ia,X Ia,Y Ia,Z)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,X)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,X,Y,Z)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, blue](C,Ia)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, orange](A,Ia)
                            \tkzFillPolygon[orange!20,opacity=0.2](A,Y,Ia,Z)
                            \tkzFillPolygon[blue!20,opacity=0.2](C,X,Ia,Z)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,X,C)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](Ia,Y,B)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](A){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ia){$J_a$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](X){$X$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](Y){$Y$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](Z){$Z$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right](X,Ia){$r_a = \frac{\Delta}{s-a}$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,B){$c$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,C){$a$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below left](B,C){$b$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>\triangle BYJ_a</m> and <m>\triangle BZJ_a</m> share all equal sides, they have equal areas. The same applies to <m>\triangle CXJ_a</m> and <m>\triangle CZJ_a</m>. Thus the area of quadrilateral <m>ABCJ_a</m> is:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \text{Area}(ABCJ_a) \amp = \Delta + 2\cdot\Delta_{BYJ_a} + 2\cdot\Delta_{CXJ_a} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \Delta + 2\cdot\frac{1}{2}BY \cdot r_a + 2\cdot\frac{1}{2}CX \cdot r_a </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \Delta + (BY + CX)r_a </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \Delta + \left(\frac{a+b-c}{2} + \frac{a+c-b}{2}\right)r_a </mrow>
                            <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq-exradius-proof-2"> \text{Area}(ABCJ_a) \amp = \Delta + a r_a </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        By equating the two expressions for the area of <m>ABCJ_a</m> from (d) and (e), show that <md>
                            r_a = \frac{\Delta}{s-a}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Equating <xref ref="eq-exradius-proof-1"/> and <xref ref="eq-exradius-proof-2"/>, we get:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> sr_a \amp = \Delta + a r_a </mrow>
                            <mrow>sr_a - ar_a \amp = \Delta</mrow>
                            <mrow>r_a \amp = \frac{\Delta}{s-a} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        as required.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Let <m>r</m> denote the <em>inradius</em> of <m>\triangle ABC</m> with sides <m>a</m>,<m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>. Denote the exradii as <m>r_a</m>, <m>r_b</m>, and <m>r_c</m>, and suppose <m>\Delta</m> is the area of <m>\triangle ABC</m>.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="exradius-reciprocal">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use <xref ref="thm-exradius"/> to prove that:
                        <md>
                            \frac{1}{r} = \frac{1}{r_a} + \frac{1}{r_b} + \frac{1}{r_c}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Recall <xref ref="thm-inscribed-circle"/>
                    </p>
                </hint>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        By <xref ref="thm-inscribed-circle"/>, <m>r = \frac{\Delta}{s}</m>. We have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \frac{1}{r_a} + \frac{1}{r_b} + \frac{1}{r_c} \amp = \frac{s-a}{\Delta} + \frac{s-b}{\Delta} +\frac{s-c}{\Delta} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{3s - (a+b+c)}{\Delta}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{3s - 2s}{\Delta}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{s}{\Delta}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{r}</mrow>
                        </md>
                        as required.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="exradius-product">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use <xref ref="thm-exradius"/> to prove that:
                        <md>
                            r\times r_a \times r_b \times r_c = \Delta^2
                        </md>
                        
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Recall Heron's formula.
                    </p>
                </hint>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Calculating the product:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> r\times r_a \times r_b \times r_c \amp = \frac{\Delta}{s} \cdot \frac{\Delta}{s-a}\cdot \frac{\Delta}{s-b}\cdot \frac{\Delta}{s-c} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{\Delta^4}{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        By Heron's formula, <m>\Delta = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</m>, so:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> r\times r_a \times r_b \times r_c \amp = \frac{\Delta^4}{\Delta^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \Delta^2</mrow>
                        </md>
                        as required.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has inradius <m>r = 2</m> cm, <m>r_a = 3</m> cm, and <m>r_b = 10</m> cm. Use <xref ref="exradius-reciprocal"/> to find <m>r_c</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr3">
                    <caption>Incircle (radius <m>r</m>) and excircles with radii <m>r_a</m> and <m>r_b</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]
                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 6/0/C, 2/4/A}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoints{I}{Xi}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xia}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](B,C,A)  \tkzGetPoints{Ib}{Xib}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)  \tkzGetPoint{FootI}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{FootIa}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ib) \tkzGetPoint{FootIb}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[green!60!black,thick](I,FootI)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,FootIa)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ib,FootIb)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,I,Ia,Ib)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$A$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above](A){$B$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](I){$r$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ia){$r_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[left](Ib){$r_b$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    We have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{r} \amp = \frac{1}{r_a} + \frac{1}{r_b} + \frac{1}{r_c} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{2} \amp = \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{10} + \frac{1}{r_c} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{r_c} \amp = \frac{2}{15} </mrow>
                        <mrow>r_c \amp = \frac{15}{2} \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular plot in Nairobi has boundary lengths <m>9</m> m, <m>12</m> m, and <m>15</m> m. A developer wants to install a circular water tank just outside the plot, touching the <m>15</m> m boundary and the extensions of the other two sides. Find the radius of the tank.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-ex4">
                    <caption>Excircle opposite <m>A</m> (the right angle) in the 9-12-15 triangle.</caption>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.2]
                        %% --- SET: right angle at A; AB=9, AC=12, BC=15 ---
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B, 0/12/C}
                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                        \tkzDefCircle[ex](C,A,B) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xa}
                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{X}
                        %% --- DRAW ---
                        \tkzDrawLine[add=1 and 0, dashed](C,A)
                        \tkzDrawLine[add=1 and 0, dashed](B,A)
                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                        \tkzDrawSegment[red,thin](Ia,X)
                        \tkzDrawCircle[blue,thick](Ia,X)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Ia,X)
                        %% --- MARK ---
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.5](B,A,C)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.4](Ia,X,B)
                        %% --- LABEL ---
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ia){$J_a$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below,pos=0.5](A,B){$9$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[left,pos=0.5](A,C){$12$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below left,pos=0.5](B,C){$15$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The excircle touching the <m>15</m> m side is opposite the vertex across from it. Label <m>a = 15</m> m, so we need <m>r_a</m>. As <m>9^2 + 12^2 = 225 = 15^2</m> <m>\triangle ABC</m> is right-angled, with area <m>\Delta = \frac{1}{2}\times 9 \times 12 = 54</m> m<m>^2</m> and semi-perimeter <m>s = \frac{9+12+15}{2} = 18</m> m. Therefore:
                    <md>
                        r_a = \frac{54}{18 - 15} = \frac{54}{3} = 18 \text{ m.}
                    </md>
                    The water tank has radius <m>18</m> m.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="excircle-triangle">
            <title>Connecting Excircles to the Incircle</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    In <xref ref="fig-incircle-excircle"/> we have constructed the three excircles for <m>\triangle ABC</m>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-excircle">
                    <caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> with 3 excircles.</caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \definecolor{triblue}{RGB}{60,120,190}
                            \definecolor{trifill}{RGB}{210,228,246}
                            \definecolor{exorange}{RGB}{243,146,30}
                            \definecolor{exfill}{RGB}{252,229,205}
                            \definecolor{trigreen}{RGB}{90,160,70}
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoint(-2,-1){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-1,2){B}
                            \tkzDefPoint(3,0){C}
                            %% --- CALCULATE: bisector direction points ---
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{iA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{iB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{eA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{eB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,C,B)\tkzGetPoint{eC}
                            %% --- centres: incentre and the three excentres ---
                            \tkzInterLL(A,iA)(B,iB)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLL(B,eB)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JA}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JB}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(B,eB)\tkzGetPoint{JC}
                            %% --- tangent feet (give each radius) ---
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{Ti}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](JA)\tkzGetPoint{Ta}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](JB)\tkzGetPoint{Tb}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](JC)\tkzGetPoint{Tc}
                            %% --- fills ---
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JC,Tc)
                            %% --- circle outlines ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JC,Tc)
                            %% --- extended sides (black) ---
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](B,C)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](C,A)
                            %% --- points + labels ---
                            \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints[fill=exorange, size=3.5pt](JA,JB,JC)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](C){$C$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](JA){$J_A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](JB){$J_B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](JC){$J_C$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="excenter-connection">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Draw lines connecting the excenters. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The lines go through the vertices of <m>\triangle ABC</m>:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-excircle-soln-1">
                    <caption>Connecting the Excenters</caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \definecolor{triblue}{RGB}{60,120,190}
                            \definecolor{trifill}{RGB}{210,228,246}
                            \definecolor{exorange}{RGB}{243,146,30}
                            \definecolor{exfill}{RGB}{252,229,205}
                            \definecolor{trigreen}{RGB}{90,160,70}
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoint(-2,-1){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-1,2){B}
                            \tkzDefPoint(3,0){C}
                            %% --- CALCULATE: bisector direction points ---
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{iA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{iB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{eA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{eB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,C,B)\tkzGetPoint{eC}
                            %% --- centres: incentre and the three excentres ---
                            \tkzInterLL(A,iA)(B,iB)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLL(B,eB)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JA}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JB}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(B,eB)\tkzGetPoint{JC}
                            %% --- tangent feet (give each radius) ---
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{Ti}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](JA)\tkzGetPoint{Ta}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](JB)\tkzGetPoint{Tb}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](JC)\tkzGetPoint{Tc}
                            %% --- fills ---
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JC,Tc)
                            %% --- external bisectors (green): the excentral triangle ---
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JA,JB)
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JB,JC)
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JC,JA)
                            %% --- circle outlines ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JC,Tc)
                            %% --- extended sides (black) ---
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](B,C)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](C,A)
                            %% --- points + labels ---
                            \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoints[fill=exorange, size=3.5pt](JA,JB,JC)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](C){$C$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](JA){$J_A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](JB){$J_B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](JC){$J_C$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Draw the incircle for <m>\triangle ABC</m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        We have drawn the incircle below:
                        <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-excircle-soln-2">
                    <caption>Incircle and Excircles</caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \definecolor{triblue}{RGB}{60,120,190}
                            \definecolor{trifill}{RGB}{210,228,246}
                            \definecolor{exorange}{RGB}{243,146,30}
                            \definecolor{exfill}{RGB}{252,229,205}
                            \definecolor{trigreen}{RGB}{90,160,70}
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \tkzDefPoint(-2,-1){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-1,2){B}
                            \tkzDefPoint(3,0){C}
                            %% --- CALCULATE: bisector direction points ---
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{iA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{iB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{eA}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{eB}
                            \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,C,B)\tkzGetPoint{eC}
                            %% --- centres: incentre and the three excentres ---
                            \tkzInterLL(A,iA)(B,iB)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLL(B,eB)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JA}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JB}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(B,eB)\tkzGetPoint{JC}
                            %% --- tangent feet (give each radius) ---
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{Ti}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](JA)\tkzGetPoint{Ta}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](JB)\tkzGetPoint{Tb}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](JC)\tkzGetPoint{Tc}
                            %% --- fills ---
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JC,Tc)
                            \tkzFillCircle[trifill](I,Ti)
                            %% --- external bisectors (green): the excentral triangle ---
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JA,JB)
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JB,JC)
                            \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JC,JA)
                            %% --- circle outlines ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JA,Ta)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JB,Tb)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JC,Tc)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[triblue, very thick](I,Ti)
                            %% --- extended sides (black) ---
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](B,C)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](C,A)
                            %% --- points + labels ---
                            \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                            \tkzDrawPoint[fill=triblue, size=3.5pt](I)
                            \tkzDrawPoints[fill=exorange, size=3.5pt](JA,JB,JC)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](C){$C$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](I){$I$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](JA){$J_A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](JB){$J_B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](JC){$J_C$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Connect the excircle centres to their opposite vertex (so <m>J_A</m> connects to <m>A</m>). What do you notice in relation to the incircle?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        These lines all go through the incentre <m>I</m>, as they are the angle bisectors of the triangle vertices.
                        <figure xml:id="fig-incircle-excircle-soln-3">
                        <caption>The Angle Bisectors and the Incircle</caption>
                        <image>
                            <latex-image>
                                \definecolor{triblue}{RGB}{60,120,190}
                                \definecolor{trifill}{RGB}{210,228,246}
                                \definecolor{exorange}{RGB}{243,146,30}
                                \definecolor{exfill}{RGB}{252,229,205}
                                \definecolor{trigreen}{RGB}{90,160,70}
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                                %% --- SET ---
                                \tkzDefPoint(-2,-1){A}
                                \tkzDefPoint(-1,2){B}
                                \tkzDefPoint(3,0){C}
                                %% --- CALCULATE: bisector direction points ---
                                \tkzDefLine[bisector](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{iA}
                                \tkzDefLine[bisector](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{iB}
                                \tkzDefLine[bisector out](B,A,C)\tkzGetPoint{eA}
                                \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,B,C)\tkzGetPoint{eB}
                                \tkzDefLine[bisector out](A,C,B)\tkzGetPoint{eC}
                                %% --- centres: incentre and the three excentres ---
                                \tkzInterLL(A,iA)(B,iB)\tkzGetPoint{I}
                                \tkzInterLL(B,eB)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JA}
                                \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(C,eC)\tkzGetPoint{JB}
                                \tkzInterLL(A,eA)(B,eB)\tkzGetPoint{JC}
                                %% --- tangent feet (give each radius) ---
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](I)\tkzGetPoint{Ti}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](JA)\tkzGetPoint{Ta}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](JB)\tkzGetPoint{Tb}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](JC)\tkzGetPoint{Tc}
                                %% --- fills ---
                                \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JA,Ta)
                                \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JB,Tb)
                                \tkzFillCircle[exfill](JC,Tc)
                                \tkzFillCircle[trifill](I,Ti)
                                %% --- external bisectors (green): the excentral triangle ---
                                \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JA,JB)
                                \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JB,JC)
                                \tkzDrawLine[trigreen, thick, add=0.2 and 0.2](JC,JA)
                                %% --- internal bisectors (red): each vertex to its opposite excentre, through I ---
                                \tkzDrawLine[red, thick, add=0.12 and 0.12](A,JA)
                                \tkzDrawLine[red, thick, add=0.12 and 0.12](B,JB)
                                \tkzDrawLine[red, thick, add=0.12 and 0.12](C,JC)
                                %% --- circle outlines ---
                                \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JA,Ta)
                                \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JB,Tb)
                                \tkzDrawCircle[exorange, very thick](JC,Tc)
                                \tkzDrawCircle[triblue, very thick](I,Ti)
                                %% --- extended sides (black) ---
                                \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](A,B)
                                \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](B,C)
                                \tkzDrawLine[very thick, add=1.4 and 1.4](C,A)
                                %% --- points + labels ---
                                \tkzDrawPoints[size=2.5pt](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoint[fill=triblue, size=3.5pt](I)
                                \tkzDrawPoints[fill=exorange, size=3.5pt](JA,JB,JC)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above left](B){$B$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](C){$C$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](I){$I$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](JA){$J_A$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below](JB){$J_B$}
                                \tkzLabelPoint[left](JC){$J_C$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    We have drawn <m>\Delta ABC</m> with sides <m>5</m> cm, <m>6</m> cm, and <m>7</m> cm, and its three excircles.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> with its excircles.</caption>
                    <image width="85%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET: a=BC=5, b=CA=6, c=AB=7 ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C}
                          \tkzDefPoint(7,0){bR}
                          \tkzDefPoint(11,0){cR}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzInterCC(B,bR)(C,cR) \tkzGetPoints{A}{Ap}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ib}{Xib}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](B,C,A) \tkzGetPoints{Ic}{Xic}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](C,A,B) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xia}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Xa}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ib) \tkzGetPoint{Xb}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](Ic) \tkzGetPoint{Xc}
                          \tkzInterLL(A,Xa)(B,Xb) \tkzGetPoint{Nagel}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircles[blue!70, thick](Ia,Xa Ib,Xb Ic,Xc)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Xa,Xb,Xc,Ia,Ib,Ic)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ic){$J_c$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ib){$J_b$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ia){$J_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Xa){$X_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](Xb){$X_b$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left](Xc){$X_c$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p> We have labelled the points of contact <m>X_a</m>, <m>X_b</m>, and <m>X_c</m> between the excircles and the triangle.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Draw lines <m>AX_a</m>, <m>BX_b</m>, and <m>CX_c</m>. What do you notice?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The three lines <m>AX_a</m>, <m>BX_b</m>, <m>CX_c</m> are concurrent; they all pass through the <term>Nagel point</term> of the triangle.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>The Nagel point: <m>AX_a</m>, <m>BX_b</m>, <m>CX_c</m> are concurrent.</caption>
                    <image width="85%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET: a=BC=5, b=CA=6, c=AB=7 ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 5/0/C}
                          \tkzDefPoint(7,0){bR}
                          \tkzDefPoint(11,0){cR}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzInterCC(B,bR)(C,cR) \tkzGetPoints{A}{Ap}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ib}{Xib}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](B,C,A) \tkzGetPoints{Ic}{Xic}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](C,A,B) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xia}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{Xa}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ib) \tkzGetPoint{Xb}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](Ic) \tkzGetPoint{Xc}
                          \tkzInterLL(A,Xa)(B,Xb) \tkzGetPoint{Nagel}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircles[blue!70, thick](Ia,Xa Ib,Xb Ic,Xc)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[red,thick](A,Xa B,Xb C,Xc)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,Xa,Xb,Xc,Nagel,Ia,Ib,Ic)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ic){$J_c$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ib){$J_b$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Ia){$J_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](Xa){$X_a$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](Xb){$X_b$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left](Xc){$X_c$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](Nagel){\footnotesize Nagel}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For a triangle of your choice:
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Construct all three excircles.</li>
                        <li>Construct the <term>nine-point circle</term> of the triangle: the circumcircle through the midpoints of the three sides.</li>
                        <li>How does the nine-point circle relate to the excircles?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The nine-point circle touches each excircle at exactly one point. This is <term>Feuerbach's theorem</term>.
                    <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr7">
                    <caption>Nine-point circle and all three excircles (Feuerbach's theorem: each excircle is internally tangent to the nine-point circle).</caption>
                    <image width="75%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 6/0/C, 1.8/4/A}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Mab}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C) \tkzGetPoint{Mbc}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,C) \tkzGetPoint{Mac}
                          \tkzDefCircle[circum](Mab,Mbc,Mac) \tkzGetPoints{N9}{N9r}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoints{Ia}{Xia}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](B,C,A) \tkzGetPoints{Ib}{Xib}
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](C,A,B) \tkzGetPoints{Ic}{Xic}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto B--C](Ia) \tkzGetPoint{FootA}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto C--A](Ib) \tkzGetPoint{FootB}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto A--B](Ic) \tkzGetPoint{FootC}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[orange,thick](N9,N9r)
                          \tkzDrawCircles[blue!70, thick](Ia,FootA Ib,FootB Ic,FootC)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,N9)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$A$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](C){$C$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above](A){$B$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above](N9){\footnotesize nine-point}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>Excircles and Direct and Transverse Tangets</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Suppose we start with two circles with centres <m>J_Q</m> and <m>J_R</m> 7 cm apart, with radii 2 and 3 cm.
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr9-setup">
                    <caption>Two circles (radii 2 and 3, centres 7 apart).</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/O1, 7/0/O2}
                          \tkzDefPoint(2,0){rO1}
                          \tkzDefPoint(10,0){rO2}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          % Internal centre of similitude P (divides O1O2 in ratio r1:r2 = 2:3)
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\pRat}{2/(2+3)}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center O1 ratio \pRat](O2) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                          % External centre of similitude E (ratio r1/(r1-r2) = -2)
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\eRat}{2/(2-3)}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center O1 ratio \eRat](O2) \tkzGetPoint{E}
                          % Transverse tangent touch-points from P
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=P](O1,rO1) \tkzGetPoints{T1a}{T1b}
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=P](O2,rO2) \tkzGetPoints{T2a}{T2b}
                          % Direct tangent touch-points from E
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=E](O1,rO1) \tkzGetPoints{Td1a}{Td1b}
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=E](O2,rO2) \tkzGetPoints{Td2a}{Td2b}
                          % Triangle vertices: Q,R = direct tangent meets transverse tangents
                          \tkzInterLL(Td1a,Td2a)(P,T1a) \tkzGetPoint{Q}
                          \tkzInterLL(Td1a,Td2a)(P,T1b) \tkzGetPoint{R}
                          % Third excircle opposite P
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](R,P,Q) \tkzGetPoints{Ip}{Xp}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](Ip) \tkzGetPoint{FootP}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawCircles[thick](O1,rO1 O2,rO2)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(O1,O2)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](O1){$J_Q$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](O2){$J_R$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Construct both <term>transverse common tangents</term> to the two circles (tangents that cross between the circles). Label their intersection point <m>P</m>.</li>
                    <li>Construct one <term>direct common tangent</term> (a tangent that does not cross between the circles). Let <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m> be the points where the direct tangent meets the transverse tangents, and draw <m>\triangle PQR</m>.</li>
                    <li>The two original circles are excircles of triangle <m>PQR</m>. Which vertices are they opposite?</li>
                    <li>Construct the third excircle of triangle <m>PQR</m> — the one opposite <m>P</m>.</li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using <xref ref="excircle-triangle"/>, if you were given two circles with direct and transverse tangents drawn, where could you draw a third circle center so that the three circles were excircles of one triangle?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig-excircle-exr9">
                    <caption>Two circles (radii 2 and 3, centres 7 apart); transverse tangents meet at <m>P</m>; triangle <m>PQR</m> formed with third excircle opposite <m>P</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/O1, 7/0/O2}
                          \tkzDefPoint(2,0){rO1}
                          \tkzDefPoint(10,0){rO2}
                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          % Internal centre of similitude P (divides O1O2 in ratio r1:r2 = 2:3)
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\pRat}{2/(2+3)}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center O1 ratio \pRat](O2) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                          % External centre of similitude E (ratio r1/(r1-r2) = -2)
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\eRat}{2/(2-3)}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center O1 ratio \eRat](O2) \tkzGetPoint{E}
                          % Transverse tangent touch-points from P
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=P](O1,rO1) \tkzGetPoints{T1a}{T1b}
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=P](O2,rO2) \tkzGetPoints{T2a}{T2b}
                          % Direct tangent touch-points from E
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=E](O1,rO1) \tkzGetPoints{Td1a}{Td1b}
                          \tkzDefTangent[from=E](O2,rO2) \tkzGetPoints{Td2a}{Td2b}
                          % Triangle vertices: Q,R = direct tangent meets transverse tangents
                          \tkzInterLL(Td1a,Td2a)(P,T1a) \tkzGetPoint{Q}
                          \tkzInterLL(Td1a,Td2a)(P,T1b) \tkzGetPoint{R}
                          % Third excircle opposite P
                          \tkzDefCircle[ex](R,P,Q) \tkzGetPoints{Ip}{Xp}
                          \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto Q--R](Ip) \tkzGetPoint{FootP}
                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          %\tkzInit[xmin=-0.5,xmax=11,ymin=-4.5,ymax=4.5]
                          %\tkzClip
                          \tkzDrawCircles[thick](O1,rO1 O2,rO2)
                          \tkzDrawLine[thick, dashed, add=0.5 and 0.5](Q,R)
                          \tkzDrawLine[thick, dashed, add=2 and 1](R,P)
                          \tkzDrawLine[thick, dashed, add=1.5 and 1](Q,P)
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[red,thick](P,Q,R)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!60,thick](Ip,FootP)
                          \tkzDrawPoints(O1,O2,P,Q,R,Ip)
                          %% --- MARK ---
                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](O1){$J_Q$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](O2){$J_R$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[below](P){$P$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right, xshift=6pt, yshift=-2pt](Q){$Q$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above left, xshift=-5pt, yshift=-3pt](R){$R$}
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](Ip){$J_P$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Construction exercise. The two transverse common tangents meet at <m>P</m>, the internal centre of similitude of the two circles — the point between them that divides the line of centres in the ratio of the radii.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Construction exercise: the direct common tangent meets the two transverse tangents at <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m>, forming the triangle <m>PQR</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each original circle is tangent to the direct tangent line (side <m>QR</m>) and to the extensions of the two sides of the triangle meeting at its adjacent vertex. This is exactly the definition of an excircle: the circle of radius <m>2</m> cm is opposite <m>Q</m>, and the circle of radius <m>3</m> cm is opposite <m>R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Construct the external bisectors of angles <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m> in triangle <m>PQR</m>; their intersection is the excenter <m>J_p</m>. Drop a perpendicular from <m>J_p</m> to one side to find the radius, then draw the excircle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            By <xref ref="excircle-triangle"/>, the lines connecting the excenters go through the original triangles vertices. In our construction, the triangle vertices were the intersection of a direct tangent with both transverse tangents (<m>R</m> and <m>Q</m>), as well as the intersection of the transverse tangent (<m>P</m>). Thus we need the line connecting the third center <m>J_P</m> to <m>J_Q</m> and <m>J_R</m> to go through <m>R</m> and <m>Q</m> respectively.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence <m>J_P</m> sits at the intersection of <m>J_QR</m> and <m>J_RQ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

